n lost, and they endure no evil. He knows that it is not one of the Seven, or the Nine, for they are accounted for. He knows that it is the One. And he has at last heard, I think, of hobbits and the Shire.<br>
            <br>
&quot;The Shire- he may be seeking for it now, if he has not already found out where it lies. Indeed, Frodo, I fear that he may even think that the long-unnoticed name of Baggins has become important.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But this is terrible!&quot; cried Frodo. &quot;Far worse than the worst that I imagined from your hints and warnings. O Gandalf, best of friends, what am I to do? For now I am really afraid. What am I to do? What a pity that Bilbo did not stab that vile creature, when he had a chance!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Pity? It was Pity that stayed his hand. Pity, and Mercy: not to strike without need. And he has been well rewarded, Frodo. Be sure that he took so little hurt from the evil, and escaped in the end, because he began his ownership of the Ring so. With Pity.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I am sorry,&quot; said Frodo. &quot;But I am frightened; and I do not feel any pity for Gollum.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You have not seen him,&quot; Gandalf broke in.<br>
<br>
&quot;No, and I don't want to,&quot; said Frodo. &quot;I can't understand you. Do you mean to say that you, and the Elves, have let him live on after all those horrible deeds? Now at any rate he is as bad as an Orc, and just an enemy. He deserves death.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Deserves it! I daresay he does. Many that live deserve death. And some that die deserve life. Can you give it to them? Then do not be too eager to deal out death in judgement. For even the very wise cannot see all ends. I have not much hope that Gollum can be cured before he dies, but there is a chance of it. And he is bound up with the fate of the Ring. My heart tells me that he has some part to play yet, for good or ill, before the end; and when that comes, the pity of Bilbo may rule the fate of many- yours not least.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The above is one of the best exchanges written by Tolkien and is likely one of the very best examples of his Christianity coming through in his writings.  I think Peter Jackson, in making the movies, understood this passage exceptionally well and was sure to incorporate this into his portrayal of Gollum.<br>
<br>
Yes, beyond a doubt, when you see the CGI figure of Gollum in the movies he is disturbing beyond words - both by his appearance and actions.  The fact that Jackson was able to create a scene (the cowering on the ground) where you start to feel pity for Gollum rather than loathing is a testimony to Jackson's ability as a director.<br>
<br>
Yes, you do need to see the vile nature of Gollum as portrayed in the movie and hate him much as Sam does.  But then you also need to see the pitiful nature of Gollum as portrayed in the movie quite effectively and feel for him as Frodo eventually does.<br>
<br>
Gollum is a hard character, both repulsive and pitiful.  The movie struck the balance so well it still amazes me - there were many, including myself, who felt that &quot;Gollum&quot; deserved an Oscar nomination.<br>
<br>
As I said before, I really was never able to feel much for Gollum simply by reading the books, even though Tolkien did do an excellent job is writing the scenes.  It was only after seeing the movie that I got the full impression of the character and Jackson really did manage to capture the side of Gollum that was to be pittied.<br>
<br>
If Jackson had watered down the repulsive nature of Gollum we would feel nothing but pity for the character, which isn't right either.  Our emotions are supposed to be torn while seeing Gollum.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I've rambled here more than enough.  Let us know when you do finally see The Two Towers and whether your opinion of Gollum differs from what it is currently.  <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man.<br>
